Takeaway: In a self-modifying system, the first version of any data consumer is always brittle against future data shapes you invent later. The maturity indicator isn't whether you built it forward-compatible from day one (impossible — you didn't know what shapes were coming), but how quickly you convert brittleness into resilience when you discover it. The right habit is: whenever you add a new variant to a data model (event type, enum variant, config field), pause and ask which consumers will choke on it before they get the chance to find out in production.

